{{italic title}} {{refimprove|date=October 2014}} '''''Bare''''' was a British [[magazine]] developed and launched as a wellbeing brand by the [[John Brown Media]] company<ref name=hodgson>{{cite news |last1=Hodgson |first1=Jessica |title=Who dares buy Bare? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/jun/04/mondaymediasection3 |accessdate=31 October 2014|work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 June 2001}}</ref> It was published from Sept/Oct 2000 to August 2001, with six issues per year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Catalogue record for ''Bare'' |url=http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?tabs=moreTab&ct=display&fn=search&doc=BLL01011166309&indx=1&recIds=BLL01011166309&recIdxs=0&elementId=0&renderMode=poppedOut&displayMode=full&frbrVersion=&dscnt=1&vl%2810130439UI0%29=title&vl%28drStartDay4%29=00&vl%28drEndMonth4%29=00&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&tab=local_tab&dstmp=1414775218926&srt=rank&mode=Advanced&vl%28drEndDay4%29=00&vl%281UIStartWith1%29=contains&tb=t&vl%2841497491UI2%29=any&vl%28freeText0%29=Bare&vid=BLVU1&vl%28freeText2%29=&vl%28drEndYear4%29=Year&frbg=&vl%28drStartMonth4%29=00&vl%2810130438UI1%29=any&vl%281UIStartWith2%29=contains&dum=true&vl%281UIStartWith0%29=contains&vl%2846690061UI3%29=journals&Submit=Search&vl%28freeText1%29=&vl%28drStartYear4%29=Year |publisher=British Library |accessdate=31 October 2014}}</ref> An early version of the magazine, then called ''Well'' was tested in market research groups in 1999 where Claudia Zeff, then art director of ''UK Gardens Illustrated'' commissioned designer, Kirsten Willey to produce a wellbeing magazine concept. It was Zeff who suggested the name change from ''Well'' to ''Bare'' after watching a [[BBC]] documentary about British architect, John Pawson.
In March 2000, [[Ilse Crawford]] – founder editor of British ''ELLE Decoration'' - was invited as editor of ''Bare'' for a summer launch.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirwan-Taylor |first1=Helen |title=At Home With: Ilse Crawford; Diplomacy in Design, Life in One Room |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/15/garden/at-home-with-ilse-crawford-diplomacy-in-design-life-in-one-room.html |accessdate=31 October 2014 |work=[[New York Times]] |date=15 May 2003}}</ref> At this time the publication was a bimonthly magazine available on news-stands internationally. The advertising department led by publisher, Honor Riley, formerly of [[Condé Nast]], secured a world first with [[Chanel]] advertising in the launch issue.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} Partnerships were garnered with Harvey Nichols and other brands with synergy. The magazine was popular amongst the design aficionado in Belgium and a copy of the Helena Christensen edition made an appearance on the ''[[Sex And The City]]'' episode, [[List of Sex and the City episodes#1.4 Season 4 (2001–02)|''Time and Punishment'']].
The magazine has been described as "speak[ing] the earnest psychobabble of the Hampstead eco-hypochondriac".<ref name=hodgson />
