'''Deborah Schofield''' is the Professor and Chair of Health Economics at the School of Public Health at the [[University of Sydney]].<ref name="UNSW">{{cite web | url=http://compare-phc.unsw.edu.au/content/professor-deborah-schofield | title=Professor Deborah Schofield | publisher=University of New South Wales | accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>

==Background==
Schofield was born in 1965 in [[Wahroonga, Sydney]]. She has worked for the Australian Government, in academia and clinical practice and is notable for establishing the health microsimulation modelling program at the National Centre for Social and Economic Modelling.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sydney.edu.au/medicine/people/academics/profiles/deborah.schofield.php | title=Professor Deborah Schofield | publisher=University of Sydney | accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acps.unsw.edu.au/acps-inaugural-symposium-speakers |title=ACPS Inaugural Symposium Speakers {{pipe}} Australian Centre for Perinatal Sciences |publisher=Australian Centre for Perinatal Sciences |accessdate=8 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108131223/http://www.acps.unsw.edu.au/acps-inaugural-symposium-speakers |archivedate=8 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> The methods for modelling public health expenditure which she established are now used by the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctc.usyd.edu.au/automated-nodes/people/deborah-schofield.aspx |title=NHMRC CTC&nbsp;— Deborah Schofield |publisher=University of Sydney |accessdate=1 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108134048/http://www.ctc.usyd.edu.au/automated-nodes/people/deborah-schofield.aspx |archivedate=8 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Prior to joining the University of Sydney, Schofield worked for a decade in senior government roles where she led the development of major new policies, continues to inform her academic career.<ref>Commonwealth of Australia, (2002), Intergenerational Report 2002-03 (health sections), Department of The Treasury, Budget paper no. 5, Canberra.</ref>

==Education==
{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2014}}
Professor Schofield began her career with a Bachelor of Speech Therapy from the University of Queensland in 1986, which she followed up with Graduate Diploma in Computing Science from the University of Canberra in 1993 and finally graduated with a PhD in Mathematics-economic modelling in 2000, also from the University of Canberra.<!--
This information will be difficult to find, but it is not unverifiable, therefore, it should be hidden and not removed
==Awards==
Price Waterhouse&nbsp;– Prize in Human Computer Interface Design, 1993.-->

==Research==
Schofield's research includes assessments of the productivity impacts of illness and she currently leads a research program at the University of Sydney on the relationship between health and social policy where health has impacts across multiple government agencies.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://sydney.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=6319 | title=Retirement funds affected by depression and mental illness&nbsp;— News and Events&nbsp;— University of Sydney | date=2 February 2011 | accessdate=8 November 2014 | author=Hollick, Victoria | publisher=University of Sydney}}</ref> The new applications of microsimulation Schofield pioneered helps to ensure health care funding is sustainable and labour force participation is maximised. This assists governments providing the information needed by policymakers who impact health, the labour market, income and taxation policy. The purpose of her research is to ensure that the health and aged care systems meet the demands of an ageing population.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://ama.com.au/ausmed/node/1688 | title=Healthy Ageing in Australia {{pipe}} Australian Medical Association | publisher=Australian Medical Association | date=23 December 2012 | accessdate=8 November 2014}}</ref> It uses data drawn from her own work, other studies and publicly available datasets in areas as diverse as IQ deficits caused by anaemia in pregnancy, poverty and mental illness,<ref name="Schofield1">Schofield D, Kelly S, Shrestha, R, Callander E, Percival R, Passey M (2011) Quantifying the effect of early retirement on the wealth of individuals with depression or other mental illness. British Journal of Psychiatry 198:123-128.</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/mental-illness-can-bring-a-massive-pay-cut/story-fn6b3v4f-1225998338683 | title=Mental illness can bring a massive pay cut {{pipe}} dailytelegraph.com.au | publisher=News Limited | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Telegraph]] | date=2 February 2011 | accessdate=8 November 2014 | author=Rose Danny}}</ref> genetic testing for highly disabling childhood genetic disorders, chronic pain<ref>Schofield D, Kelly S, Shrestha R, Callander E, Passey M, Percival R (2012) The Impact of Back Problems on Retirement Wealth Pain 153(1):203-10.</ref> and whole genome sequencing.

