[[File:Полоскание. 2013.jpg|thumb|''Gargling'' by Pavel Otdelnov]]
'''Gargling''' (same root as 'gurgle') is the act of bubbling liquid in the [[mouth]]. Vibration caused by the muscles in the throat and back of the mouth cause the liquid to bubble and flurry around inside the mouth cavity.

A traditional home remedy of gargling warm saltwater is sometimes recommended to soothe a sore throat. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.webmd.com/cold-and-flu/features/does-gargling-wlth-salt-water-ease-a-sore-throat#1|title=Does Gargling With Salt Water Ease a Sore Throat?|publisher=WebMD|author=Chris C. Anderson|date=2018}}</ref>

A study in [[Japan]] has shown that gargling water a few times a day will lower the chance of [[upper respiratory infection]]s such as [[common cold|colds]], though some medical authorities are skeptical.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Does Gargling With Water Prevent Colds?|url=http://www.webmd.com/cold-and-flu/news/20051020/does-gargling-with-water-prevent-colds|publisher=WebMD|first=Salynn|last=Boyles|date=2005-10-19|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref>

